val topology.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 13 Jun 2013 15:35:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-06-14"}
{"id":"1306.3142","submitter":"Marco Tomamichel","authors":"Martin M\\\"uller-Lennert, Fr\\'ed\\'eric Dupuis, Oleg Szehr, Serge Fehr,\n  Marco Tomamichel","title":"On quantum Renyi entropies: a new generalization and some properties","comments":"v1: contains several conjectures; v2: conjectures are resolved - see\n  also arXiv:1306.5358 and arXiv:1306.5920; v3: published version","journal-ref":"J. Math. Phys. 54, 122203 (2013)","doi":"10.1063/1.4838856","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cs.IT math-ph math.IT math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Renyi entropies constitute a family of information measures that\ngeneralizes the well-known Shannon entropy, inheriting many of its properties.\nThey appear in the form of unconditional and conditional entropies, relative\nentropies or mutual information, and have found many applications in\ninformation theory and beyond. Various generalizations of Renyi entropies to\nthe quantum setting have been proposed, most notably Petz's quasi-entropies and\nRenner's conditional min-, max- and collision entropy. Here, we argue that\nprevious quantum extensions are incompatible and thus unsatisfactory.\n  We propose a new quantum generalization of the family of Renyi entropies that\ncontains the von Neumann entropy, min-entropy, collision entropy and the\nmax-entropy as special cases, thus encompassing most quantum entropies in use\ntoday. We show several natural properties for this definition, including\ndata-processing inequalities, a duality relation, and an entropic uncertainty\nrelation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 13 Jun 2013 15:36:33 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 26 Jun 2013 17:43:31 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 18 Nov 2013 08:06:34 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Mon, 27 Jan 2014 06:13:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-01-28"}
